    <section class="method-section">
        <h2>The Orchestration Wisdom System (OWS)</h2>
        <p>
            Every pattern on this platform follows the Orchestration Wisdom System—a structured
            approach to analyzing and documenting operational problems as orchestration gaps.
        </p>

        <h3>Core Components</h3>
        <ul class="method-list">
            <li><strong>Hook:</strong> The recognizable pain point that draws you in</li>
            <li><strong>Problem in One Minute:</strong> Context and current-state clarity</li>
            <li><strong>As-Is Diagram:</strong> Visual representation of the broken state</li>
            <li><strong>Orchestrated Diagram:</strong> The transformed state with structure</li>
            <li><strong>Decision Point:</strong> The critical choice that unlocks improvement</li>
            <li><strong>Metrics & SLAs:</strong> How to measure success</li>
            <li><strong>Implementation Checklist:</strong> Concrete steps to execute</li>
            <li><strong>Orchestration Scorecard:</strong> Multi-dimensional quality assessment</li>
            <li><strong>Closing Insight:</strong> The takeaway that sticks</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
        <h2>High Quality Orchestration (HQO)</h2>
        <p>
            Not all orchestration diagrams are created equal. HQO is our rubric for evaluating
            pattern quality across eight dimensions:
        </p>

        <table class="hqo-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Dimension</th>
                    <th>What It Measures</th>
                    <th>Max Score</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Ownership</td>
                    <td>Clear assignment of responsibility</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Time/SLA</td>
                    <td>Explicit timing and deadline tracking</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Capacity</td>
                    <td>Resource awareness and load balancing</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Visibility</td>
                    <td>Observable state and progress tracking</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Customer Loop</td>
                    <td>Proactive communication mechanisms</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Escalation</td>
                    <td>Defined escalation paths and triggers</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Handoffs</td>
                    <td>Structured knowledge transfer</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Documentation</td>
                    <td>Artifact creation and preservation</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <p class="method-note">
            <strong>Quality Gate:</strong> Patterns must score ≥30/40 total, with no dimension below 3.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
        <h2>Diagram Budget Constraints</h2>
        <p>
            Simplicity is enforced through strict diagram budgets. These constraints ensure
            diagrams remain comprehensible and actionable:
        </p>

        <ul class="method-list">
            <li>≤ 7 actors (participants)</li>
            <li>≤ 18 total steps</li>
            <li>≤ 2 alt blocks (conditional branches)</li>
            <li>≤ 8 steps per alt branch</li>
            <li>No nested alt blocks</li>
            <li>Concise, verb-led messages</li>
            <li>Limited and short notes</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            If your diagram exceeds these limits, it's a signal to decompose the pattern into
            multiple related patterns or focus on a narrower scope.
        </p>
    </section>

